Question A: A battlefield sensor records signal deviation values every hour. Positive values 
indicate noise spikes, negative values indicate signal drops. The readings are stored in 
memory as an integer array. Given Data Signal = { 5, -3, 12, -7, 9, 0, -2, 15 } N = 8 
Problem Statement Write a RISC-V assembly program using RARS to: 1. Count the number 
of stable readings (values between -5 and +5, inclusive). 
2. Calculate the net signal deviation (sum of all positive values minus sum of all negative 
values). 
3. Determine the number of signal drop events (values less than 0). 
4. Find the first occurrence index of a signal spike (value greater than 10). If no such value 
exists, store -1. 
Constraints Use loops to traverse the array. Use arithmetic, comparison, and conditional 
branching instructions. Handle negative numbers correctly. Do not use pseudo instructions 
beyond standard RISC-V. The program must run correctly in RARS. 
.data 
Signal: .word 5, -3, 12, -7, 9, 0, -2, 15 
N: .word 8 
stableCount: .word 0 
dropCount: .word 0 
netDeviation: .word 0 
spikeIndex: .word -1 
newline: .asciiz "\n" 
.text 
.globl main 
main: 
li t2, 0 
li t3, 0 
la t0, Signal 
lw t1, N 
li t4, 0 
li t5, 0 
li t6, 0 
li s1, -1 
li s2, -1 
loop: 
beq t2, t1, finish 
lw s0, 0(t0) 
li s3, -5 
blt s0, s3, checkDrop 
li s3, 5 
bgt s0, s3, checkDrop 
addi t3, t3, 1 
checkDrop: 
blt s0, zero, dropEvent 
j checkPositive 
dropEvent: 
addi t4, t4, 1 
add t6, t6, s0 
j checkSpike 
checkPositive: 
bgt s0, zero, positiveValue 
j checkSpike 
positiveValue: 
add t5, t5, s0 
li s3, 10 
ble s0, s3, next 
checkSpike: 
 
    bne s1, s2, next 
 
    mv s1, t2 
 
next: 
 
    addi t0, t0, 4 
    addi t2, t2, 1 
 
    j loop 
 
finish: 
 
    sub s4, t5, t6 
 
    la s5, stableCount 
    sw t3, 0(s5) 
 
    la s5, dropCount 
    sw t4, 0(s5) 
 
    la s5, netDeviation 
    sw s4, 0(s5) 
 
    la s5, spikeIndex 
    sw s1, 0(s5) 
 
    mv a0, t3 
    li a7, 1 
    ecall 
 
    la a0, newline 
    li a7, 4 
    ecall 
 
    mv a0, s4 
    li a7, 1 
    ecall 
 
    la a0, newline 
    li a7, 4 
    ecall 
 
mv a0, t4 
li a7, 1 
ecall 
la a0, newline 
li a7, 4 
ecall 
mv a0, s1 
li a7, 1 
ecall 
la a0, newline 
li a7, 4 
ecall 
li a7, 10 
ecall 
 
 
B Question B: Write a RISC-V assembly program using RARS to: - Check whether N is even or 
odd - Check whether N is prime - Check whether N equals factorial of any integer Constraints 
• Use arithmetic instructions only • Avoid pseudo instructions beyond standard RISC-V • 
Program must execute correctly in RARS 
 
 
Code with comments: 
 
.data 
N: .word 120              # Example input (120 is even, not prime, and 5!) 
isEven: .word 0           # 1 if even, 0 if odd 
 
isPrime: .word 0          # 1 if prime, 0 if not 
isFactorial: .word 0      # 1 if N = x!, 0 if not 
 
.text 
.globl main 
main: 
    lw t0, N              # Load N into t0 
     
    # ---- 1. Check Even or Odd ---- 
    # Logic: (N / 2) * 2 == N? 
    li t1, 2 
    div t2, t0, t1        # t2 = N / 2 
    mul t2, t2, t1        # t2 = (N / 2) * 2 
    beq t2, t0, set_even 
    li t1, 0              # It is odd 
    j store_even 
set_even: 
    li t1, 1              # It is even 
store_even: 
    la t2, isEven 
    sw t1, 0(t2) 
 
    # ---- 2. Check Prime ---- 
    # Logic: Loop from 2 to N-1. If N % i == 0, not prime. 
    li t1, 1              # Default isPrime = 1 
    li t2, 2              # i = 2 
    blt t0, t2, not_prime # If N < 2, not prime 
prime_loop: 
    beq t2, t0, store_prime # If i == N, finished (is prime) 
     
    # Remainder logic: N - ((N / i) * i) 
    div t3, t0, t2        # t3 = N / i 
    mul t3, t3, t2        # t3 = (N / i) * i 
    sub t3, t0, t3        # t3 = remainder 
     
    beq t3, zero, not_prime 
    addi t2, t2, 1        # i++ 
    j prime_loop 
not_prime: 
    li t1, 0 
store_prime: 
    la t2, isPrime 
    sw t1, 0(t2) 
 
 
    # ---- 3. Check Factorial ---- 
    # Logic: Keep multiplying 1 * 2 * 3... until result >= N 
    li t1, 1              # current_factorial = 1 
    li t2, 1              # counter = 1 
fact_loop: 
    beq t1, t0, set_fact  # If current_factorial == N, is factorial 
    bgt t1, t0, not_fact  # If current_factorial > N, not factorial 
     
    addi t2, t2, 1        # counter++ 
    mul t1, t1, t2        # current_factorial *= counter 
    j fact_loop 
set_fact: 
    li t3, 1 
    j store_fact 
not_fact: 
    li t3, 0 
store_fact: 
    la t4, isFactorial 
    sw t3, 0(t4) 
 
    # ---- Exit ---- 
    li a7, 10 
    ecall 
 
 
